RATE SCHEDULE TRANSPORTATION SERVICE ACCESS I. AVAILABILITY 1.1 This Rate Schedule is available for the Transportation of Gas by Southwest Gas Corporation (the Transporter) for any party (the Shipper), under the following conditions: (a) Shipper submits a valid request as defined in Section 7 of the General Terms and Conditions of the Statement of Operating Conditions and enters into a contract with Transporter for Rate Schedule TS Access service in the form of the Transportation Service Agreement (Agreement) set forth in the Statement of Operating Conditions; (b) Transporter determines that sufficient available and uncommitted capacity exists on its system or parts thereof (including Receipt and Delivery Points) to perform the Transportation service requested; and (c) Shippers Receipt Points are limited to Gas production sources connected to Transporters Arizona System. II. APPLICABILITY AND CHARACTER OF SERVICE 2.1 This rate schedule shall apply to the Transportation of Gas by Transporter pursuant to an Agreement executed by Transporter and Shipper providing for Transportation service each Day up to the Maximum Daily Quantity (MDQ) and shall be subject to the provision of the Agreement, this Rate Schedule TS Access, and the General Terms and Conditions. 2.2 Service hereunder shall consist of: (a) the receipt of daily quantities of Gas by Transporter from Shipper plus Fuel Use and LUFG at the Receipt Point(s) up to the MDQ specified in the Agreement and as are nominated by Shipper and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 8 of the General Terms and Conditions; (b) the Transportation of such quantities of Gas by Transporter under the terms of this rate schedule and the General Terms and Conditions; and (c) the delivery to Shipper or for Shippers account at the Delivery Point(s) thermally equivalent quantities of Gas equal to the quantities received less applicable Fuel Use and LUFG. 2.3 Transporters obligations shall consist of: (a) Transporter shall exercise reasonable diligence to provide continuous service to Shipper. Transporter shall not be liable for interruptions or for any loss or damage occasioned thereby, whether such interruptions occurred with or without notice to Shipper. (b) Transporter shall not be responsible for any damage or claim of damages attributable to any interruption or discontinuation of service resulting from any cause against which Transporter could not have reasonably foreseen or made provision for. (c) Transporter has the right to suspend service temporarily for the purpose of making necessary repairs, maintenance, or improvements to its systems. When this is necessary, Transporter will endeavor to give affected Shippers reasonable notice where circumstances permit and will proceed with work with reasonable diligence. (d) Transporter shall not be responsible for any damage or claim of damage attributable to curtailment of service. (e) Transporters liability, if any, for its gross negligence or willful misconduct is not limited by this rate schedule. With respect to any claim or suit, by Shipper or by any others, for damages associated with the establishment, interruption, resumption, and termination of service to Shipper, Transporters liability shall not exceed an amount equal to the proportionate charge for the service for the period during which service was affected. Transporter shall not be liable for any special, indirect, or consequential damages whatsoever including, but not limited to, loss of profits or revenue, loss of use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment, overtime, business interruption, spoilage of goods or claims of customers of Shipper or other economic harm. III. RECEIPT AND DELIVERY POINTS 3.1 Shipper shall tender all Gas at the Receipt Point(s) specified in Shippers Agreement. 3.2 Transporter shall tender all Gas delivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s) as specified in Shippers Agreement. 3.3 Transporter and Shipper may add or delete Receipt and Delivery Point(s) to the Agreement from time-to-time by mutual agreement, subject to Section 7 of the General Terms and Conditions, provided Transporter determines that it has sufficient available and uncommitted capacity to provide service at such point(s). IV. RATES AND CHARGES 4.1 Transporter elected to provide 18 C.F.R. § 284.224 Transportation service utilizing the rates approved by the FERC pursuant to 18 C.F.R. §§ 284.123 (b)(1)(ii) and 284.123(b)(2)(i). All charges for Transportation service under this rate schedule shall be stated on the statement of Currently Effective Rates sheet of the Statement of Operating Conditions on file with the FERC. 4.2 For all service rendered under this rate schedule, Shipper shall pay Transporter each month (a) Usage Charge ¿ A charge equal to the product of the applicable usage rate(s) and the total quantities of Gas delivered by Transporter to Delivery Point(s) during the Billing Month; (b) Other Fees and Charges ¿ Other fees, charges, and penalties which may be assessed as provided by the Statement of Operating Conditions or which may be permitted by the FERC. (c) All sales, use, excise or other taxes and fees that are legally effective and applicable to the service provided. 4.3 Fuel Use and Lost and Unaccounted For Gas (LUFG) retention. Transporter shall retain applicable Fuel Use and LUFG in kind. The amount of Gas for Fuel Use and LUFG is determined in accordance with Section 8 of the General Terms and Conditions. The charges for LUFG, if invoiced, will be equal to the quantity of Gas lost multiplied by the actual cost of replacing such Gas. 4.4 Discounted Rates. Transporter shall have no obligation to offer its service at rates less than its currently effective maximum rates. Transporter may at any time and from time-to-time agree to charge an amount less than the currently effective maximum rate(s) for service provided to a Shipper. Transporter shall not apply this provision in an unduly discriminatory manner, or in a manner contrary to FERCs regulations. 4.5 Rate Adjustment. It is agreed that Transporter may make such adjustments to the Transportation rates provided herein as necessary to assure Transporter fair and equitable rates and may make such changes to this Statement of Operating Conditions as necessary to assure reasonable terms hereunder, subject to approval by the FERC or other governing body having authority, if any be required. V. TRANSPORTATION GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS 5.1 The provisions of the General Terms and Conditions, as such provisions may be amended from time-to-time, are hereby incorporated by reference and made part of this Rate Schedule TS Access, and shall apply to service rendered hereunder, as though stated herein. If, and to the extent, the provisions of this rate schedule conflict with the provisions of said General Terms and Conditions, the provisions of this Rate Schedule shall prevail. VI. TITLE TO GAS 6.1 Title to all Gas delivered by Shipper for Transporter for Transportation under this rate schedule shall remain with Shipper at all times during Transportation by Transporter.

GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS 1. DEFINITIONS 1.1 ACC: The Arizona Corporation Commission. The regulatory authority of the State of Arizona having jurisdiction over the public service corporations operating in Arizona. 1.2 Billing Month: The period between any two regular readings of the Transporters meter at intervals of approximately 30 days. 1.3 Btu: One British thermal unit. 1.4 Business Day: Monday through Friday, excluding all holidays observed by the Intercontinental Exchange for the trading of physical US natural gas. 1.5 Contract Year: The ensuing 12 months from the starting date on a contract. 1.6 Day: A period of 24-consecutive hours, within one calendar day. 1.7 Dekatherm (Dth): The quantity of heat energy which is equivalent to one MMBtu. 1.8 Delivery Point: The point or points of interconnection between Transporters System and the pipeline(s) or other connection(s) to which Transporter is to redeliver Shippers Gas hereunder. 1.9 FERC: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any commission, agency, or other governmental body succeeding to the power of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.10 Fuel Use: The Gas consumed by Transporters equipment necessary to provide Transportation service. 1.11 Gas: Any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and noncombustible gases in a gaseous state, consisting predominantly of methane, including natural gas, casing head gas, and gas from biogenic processes that meets the quality specifications of the pipeline into which it is being injected. 1.12 Gas Day: A period of 24-consecutive hours beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time (CCT). Clock Time indicates that the Transporter will adjust its Gas Day to reflect changes for Daylight Savings Time. 1.13 Lost and Unaccounted For Gas or LUFG: Gas that is lost and unaccounted for through the normal operation of Transporters system. 1.14 MAOP: The maximum allowable operating pressure of Transporters system as calculated under the regulation of the United States Department of Transportation. 1.15 Maximum Daily Quantity: The quantity of Gas that Shipper shall be entitled to nominate for Transportation service pursuant to and as set forth in Shippers Agreement. 1.16 Maximum Delivery Obligation: The maximum quantity of Gas that Transporter will deliver each Day pursuant to and as set forth in Shippers Agreement. 1.17 Maximum Receipt Obligation: The maximum quantity of Gas that Transporter is obligated to receive each Day pursuant to and as set forth in Shippers Agreement. 1.18 Mcf: 1,000 cubic feet of Gas. 1.19 MMBtu: The quantity of heat energy equivalent to 1,000,000 Btu. All references to MMBtu shall be deemed equivalent to Dth. 1.20 Month: The period beginning at 7:00 am Pacific clock time on the first Day of a calendar month and ending at the same hour on the first Day of the next succeeding calendar month. 1.21 Operational Flow Orders (OFO): An operational flow order is an order issu ed to alleviate conditions, inter alia, which threaten or could threaten the safe operations or system integrity of the transportation service providers system or to maintain operations required to provide efficient and reliable service. Whenever a Transporter experiences these conditions, any pertinent order should be referred to as an Operational Flow Order. 1.22 Psia: Absolute pressure measured in pounds per square inch. 1.23 Point Operator: The entity responsible for the operation of an interconnection between Transporter and another entity. 1.24 Receipt Point: The point or points of interconnection between Transporters system and Shipper. Receipt Point(s) are limited to Gas production sites located in Arizona at points on Transporters system. 1.25 Renewable Natural Gas (RNG): A biogas which has been upgraded to pipeline quality gas by increasing the percentage of methane in biogas by removing carbon dioxide and other trace components and adding a warning odorant. When upgraded, it is possible to distribute via the existing natural gas pipeline system. Transporter may limit the maximum quantity by volumetric percentage of, or prohibit, certain constituents specific to RNG in a separate agreement to ensure merchantability of the RNG and that the RNG may be accepted into Transporters system. 1.26 Shipper: Any entity that has entered into an Agreement with Transporter for the purpose of transporting Gas through Transporters System. 1.27 System: The natural gas transmission, distribution, and related facilities owned by Transporter within the State of Arizona. 1.28 Thermally Equivalent Quantities: The sum of the quantities of Gas measured as expressed in Dekatherms received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) during any given period of time, less LUFG. 1.29 Transportation: The movement of Gas between Receipt and Delivery Points which can occur by the physical flow of Gas or by providing a quantity of Gas at Shippers Delivery Point(s) by nomination of thermally equivalent Gas provided by Transporter. 1.30 Transportation Service Agreement (Agreement): A legally binding written agreement between Shipper and Transporter which sets forth the obligations of Transporter to provide Transportation service on Transporters system and Shippers related obligations. 1.31 Transporter: Southwest Gas Corporation. 1.32. Wobbe Number: Wobbe number, also known as the Wobbe Index, is an indicator of the interchangeability of natural gas to other forms of fuel gases, such as biogas. 2. GENERAL OPERATING PROVISIONS 2.1 General Operating Provisions. Transporter will transport Gas through its system on an interruptible basis. The ability of Transporter to provide Transportation service will be determined based on a potential Shippers proposed location and Maximum Daily Quantity. 2.2 Jurisdiction. Transportation under an intrastate service agreement that is subject to the ACCs jurisdiction shall be transported exclusively for intrastate purposes and under no circumstances will such Gas be transported to or delivered into an interstate facility. 2.3 Multiple Transportation Service Agreements. Should a Shipper require both interstate and intrastate service from Transporter, Shipper is not allowed to combine contracts for interstate services with contracts for intrastate services. Any Shipper requesting interstate and intrastate Transportation service shall have separate contracts for each activity. 2.4 Service under these General Terms and Conditions and applicable tariffs may be interrupted by Transporter at any time, without liability; all as set forth in Section 8 of these General Terms and Conditions. 2.5 Service hereunder is subject to interruption by Transporter, without liability, as set forth in Section 8 of the General Terms and Conditions and may be interrupted whenever to provide State regulated service, a higher priority of service, or to maintain the integrity of Transporters system or any part thereof. 3. GOVERNMENT REGULATIONS AND REQUIREMENTS 3.1 Government Regulations and Requirements. Any and all service transactions hereunder must be interstate service eligible under, and shall be fully subject to, the applicable requirements of Section 284.224 of the FERCs rules and regulations; Shippers request for service shall constitute its warranty that Shipper satisfies such requirements, and Transporter shall have the right to request information from any Shipper to verify the eligibility thereunder. 4. MEASUREMENT 4.1 Unit of Volume. The unit of volume shall be one Dth of Gas at a temperature base of 60 degrees Fahrenheit and a pressure base of 14.73 Psia, and all volumes shall be converted from actual conditions to these standard bases in accordance with the Ideal Gas Laws, corrected for supercompressibility in accordance with American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 8, as amended from time-to-time, unless otherwise agreed. 4.2 Atmospheric Pressure. Atmospheric Pressure is defined as the average atmospheric pressure based upon the elevation above sea level and calculated by the formula expressed in the AGA Report No. 3 as amended from time-to-time. 4.3 Quantity and Heating Value Determination. The quantity and heating value of Gas received and delivered pursuant to this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be determined as follows: (a) For the purpose of measurement and meter calibration, the average absolute atmospheric pressure for each Point of Delivery and Receipt shall be based upon the actual elevation or location of the meter at the Point of Delivery or Receipt above mean sea level. (b) The temperature of the Gas passing through the metering equipment shall, when deemed necessary for computing Gas quantities, be determined for any Day by the continuous use of a recording thermometer or its equivalent so installed that it may properly record the temperature of the Gas flowing through the metering equipment. The arithmetic average of the temperature recorded each Day or the continuous instantaneous temperature measurement shall be used in computing Gas quantity. (c) The specific gravity of the Gas passing through the metering equipment shall be determined for any one Day by the use of a Gas chromatograph recording continuously, unless otherwise agreed. The arithmetic average of the specific gravity of the Gas or the continuous instantaneous specific gravity measurement may be applied to metering equipment to provide the quantity computation. (d) The deviation of the Gas from Ideal Gas Laws shall be calculated according to the recommendations of the AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 8 ANSI/API 2530, as amended from time-to-time, unless otherwise agreed. (e) The Gross Heating Value shall be determined by using a suitably located and reasonably acceptable calorimeter or calculation from fractional analysis by an acceptable chromatograph. 4.4 Measuring Equipment. Transporter, or Transporters designee, will install, maintain and operate measuring stations and equipment by which the quantities of Gas delivered hereunder shall be determined. The Gas delivered hereunder shall be measured in accordance with the latest approved methods in use by the industry. (a) Where used, turbine meters shall be installed and operated in accordance with the AGA Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 7, as amended from time-to-time, unless otherwise agreed. (b) Where used, ultrasonic meters shall be installed and operated in accordance with the AGA Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 9, as amended from time-to-time, unless otherwise agreed. (c) Where used, other types of measurement devices or instruments, the installation and operation of such facilities shall be in accordance with terms and procedures reasonably acceptable to Transporter, in view of its operational requirements and constraints. (d) Shipper may install check measuring equipment, provided that such equipment shall be so installed as not to interfere with the operations of Transporter. 4.5 Calibration and Test of Meters. The accuracy of all measuring equipment shall be verified by the owner at a reasonable interval and, if requested, in the presence of representatives of the other party, but neither Transporter nor Shipper shall be required to verify the accuracy of such equipment more frequently than once annually. Any additional requests for accuracy verification will be paid in advance, by Shipper. Such payments are non-refundable unless the test result is an As Found accuracy error in excess of allowable limits. If either party at any time desires a special test of any measuring equipment, or if either party at any time observes an error in any such measuring equipment, it will promptly notify the other party, and the parties shall then cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment. 4.6 Correction of Metering Errors. If, upon any test, any measuring equipment is found to be in error, such errors shall be considered in a practical manner in computing the deliveries. If the resultant error in the computed deliveries is not more than three percent, then previous deliveries corrected in such a manner shall be considered accurate. All equipment shall, in any case, be adjusted at the time of test to record correctly. If, however, the resultant error in computed deliveries exceeds three percent at a recording corresponding to the average hourly rate of Gas flow for the period since the last preceding test, previous recordings of such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period which is known definitely or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period extending over one half of the time elapsed since the date of the last test, not exceeding a correction period of 16 Days. 4.7 Failure of Measuring Equipment. In the event any measuring equipment is out of service or is found registering inaccurately, and the error is not determinable by test, previous recordings or deliveries through such equipment shall be estimated: (a) By using the registration of any check meter or meters if installed and accurately registering, or in the absence of (a) then: (b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, special test or mathematical calculation, or in the absence of both (a) and (b) then: (c) By estimating the quantity of delivery by deliveries during period under similar conditions when the meter was registering accurately. The estimated reading so determined shall be used in determining the quantity of Gas delivered for any known or agreed upon applicable period. In case the period is not known or agreed upon, such estimated deliveries shall be used in determining the quantity of Gas delivered hereunder during the latter half of the period beginning on the date of the immediately preceding test and ending on the date the measuring equipment has been adjusted to record accurately; the recordings of the measuring equipment during the first half of said period shall be considered accurate in computing deliveries. 4.8 Preservation of Records. Transporter and Shipper shall preserve for a period of at least three years, or such other longer period as may be required by public authority, all test data, charts, and other similar records. 5. GAS QUALITY 5.1 Gas Quality. All Gas received into or delivered from Transporters System shall be pipeline quality Gas and shall meet the quality specifications set forth in Section 5.2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, as well as, any other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter. Shipper warrants that the Gas tendered for transport hereunder shall meet the specifications set forth in this section. Transporter may reject Gas tendered or delivered by Shipper that fails to conform to the quality specifications provided in this Statement of Operating Conditions, any other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter, or which, in Transporters reasonable judgment, may cause harm to its facilities or diminish the quality of Gas in its system. Transporter may under all circumstances subject, or permit the subjection of, the Gas to compression, cooling, cleaning, products extraction and other processes. 5.2 General Specifications. Shipper warrants that all Gas received by Transporter at any Receipt Point(s) shall conform to the following specifications and must be, in Transporters reasonable judgment, otherwise merchantable: (a) Liquids - The hydrocarbon dewpoint of the Gas tendered shall not exceed twenty (20) degrees Fahrenheit as calculated from the Gas composition and shall be free of water and hydrocarbons in liquid form at the temperature and pressure at which the Gas is received. The Gas shall in no event contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per million standard cubic feet. (b) Total Sulfur - The Gas shall not contain more than five (5) grains of total sulfur, which includes hydrogen sulfide, carbonyl sulfide, carbon disulfide, mercaptans, and mono-, di- and poly-sulfides, per one hundred (100) standard cubic feet. The Gas shall also meet the following individual specifications: (i) Hydrogen Sulfide - The Gas shall not contain more than one-quarter (0.25) grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) standard cubic feet. (ii) Mercaptan (RSH): 0.75 grains per 100 scf (iii) Organic Sulfur (OS): 1.25 grains per 100 scf (c) Oxygen - The oxygen content shall not exceed two-tenths of one percent (0.2%) by volume and every reasonable effort shall be made to keep the Gas delivered free of oxygen. (d) Carbon Dioxide - The Gas shall not have a carbon dioxide content in excess of two percent (2%) by volume. (e) Nitrogen - The Gas shall not have a nitrogen content in excess of three percent (3%) by volume. (f) Inerts - The Gas shall not at any time contain in excess of three percent (3%) total inerts (the total combined carbon dioxide, nitrogen, helium, oxygen, and any other diluent compound) by volume. (g) Dust, Gums and Solid Matter - The Gas shall be commercially free of dust, gums and other solid matter. (h) Heating Value - The heating value of Gas tendered to Transporter shall have a minimum of 976/Btu per standard cubic foot of natural gas. (i) Temperature - The Gas received by Transporter shall be at temperatures not in excess of one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120°F) nor less than fifty degrees Fahrenheit (50°F). (j) Deleterious Substances - The Gas shall not contain deleterious substances in concentrations that are hazardous to health, injurious to pipeline facilities or adversely affect merchantability. (k) Wobbe number: maximum Wobbe number 1385 minimum Wobbe number 1280 Wobbe number BTU/scf/SG scf standard cubic foot of natural gas SG specific gravity with respect to air 5.3 Right to Commingle. Transporter shall have the unqualified right to commingle Gas received for service hereunder with Gas from other sources. Accordingly, Gas received by Transporter shall be subject to such changes as may result from such commingling and Transporter shall, notwithstanding any other provisions herein, be under no obligation to deliver for Shippers account Gas identical to that received by Transporter. Subject to other terms and provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions, Transporter will transport and tender for delivery for the account of Shipper such Thermally Equivalent Quantities of Gas, less Fuel Use and LUFG, as it receives for such Shippers account. 5.4 Right of Refusal. If the Gas tendered for Transportation by Shipper fails at any time to conform to any of the specifications set forth herein above, then Transporter shall so notify Shipper thereof and Transporter thereupon may, at its option and in addition to any other remedies available to Transporter, refuse to accept delivery pending correction by Shipper. 5.5 Indemnity to Transporter. Shipper agrees that it will indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of any adverse claims by any pipeline delivering to or receiving Gas from Transporter relating to or arising from Gas not meeting the quality specifications herein (unless same was caused by the gross negligence of Transporter) or for payments for such other pipelines services for or on behalf of Shipper. Additionally, and not withstanding any language or provision to the contrary, Shipper agrees that it will indemnify Transporter and save Shipper harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of any claims by any other person or entity relating to or arising from Gas tendered by Shipper to Transporter not meeting the quality specifications herein. 5.6 Acceptance of Off-Specification Gas. In the event that the Gas being delivered does not conform to the standards outlined above, Transporter may, in a not unduly discriminatory manner accept receipt of such Gas or restrict or refuse any volumes that are non-conforming or deficient, but such acceptance does not operate as a waiver of the Gas quality specifications and further provided that Transporter may decline to accept such Gas that does not comply with the Gas quality specifications at any time; regardless of previously having accepted such non-conforming Gas. Transporters acceptance of such Gas that does not comply with the Gas quality specifications shall not obligate Transporter to accept subsequent Gas from Shipper that does not comply with the Gas quality specifications. 6. CONDITIONS OF RECEIPT 6.1 Receipt Pressure. Shipper shall tender for delivery and Transporter shall receive the Gas at the working pressures available in Transporters system at the Receipt Point(s) from time-to-time. In no event, however, shall Shipper be obligated to tender for delivery or shall Transporter be obligated to receive Gas at a pressure greater than the maximum pressure specified in the applicable Agreement or any other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter for operation at the Receipt Point(s). 6.2 Receipt Point. The Receipt Point(s) shall be limited to Gas production sites located in Arizona at points on Transporters System. 6.3 Facilities. Unless otherwise provided in the applicable Agreement, any measurement and/or appurtenant facilities required at the receipt and/or delivery point(s) shall be installed, owned, operated and maintained by Transporter. Shipper may be required to reimburse Transporter for the actual costs of any facilities acquired or installed by Transporter which are necessary to receive, monitor, measure, transport, store, or deliver Gas to or for the account of Shipper, including without limitation, right-of-way costs, loss of revenues if the installation requires the interruption of any services, and overhead charges incurred as a result of the installation of any such facilities . 7. PROCEDURES FOR REQUESTING SERVICE 7.1 Request for Service. All Shippers or potential shippers requesting Transportation service must submit a valid request pursuant to Section 7.4 hereof for such service. A request shall be considered valid as of the date received if it contains adequate information with respect to all of the items specified in Section 7.4, subject to any necessary verification, and contains the other applicable information required by this Section 7. 7.2 Services Needing a Request. A Shipper or a potential Shipper must submit a valid request for any of the following: (a) A request for Transporter to commence service for Shipper. (b) A request for an increase in Shippers contract quantity. (c) A request by an existing Shipper to add new Primary Receipt or Primary Delivery Point capacity under an existing Agreement. (d) A request by an existing Shipper to extend or renew an Agreement that has or will expire and terminate by its own terms. 7.3 Automatic Request for Service. A request by an existing Shipper to extend the term of an Agreement that contains an evergreen clause or that otherwise provides for automatic renewal or extension of service shall not necessitate the submission of a request for service as required in this Section 7, provided that Shipper notifies Transporter of such renewal or extension in accordance with the terms of the applicable Agreement. 7.4 Service Request Information. All requests for service shall be submitted in writing to Transporter and shall contain the following information: (a) Identity of Shipper The exact legal name, type of legal entity, type of company, state of incorporation or state of qualification to do business, mailing and street address and the name, phone number, and fax number of person(s) to contact regarding the service requested. If the person or entity requesting service is acting as an agent, then the exact name and address of the agents principal and written proof of the agency must also be provided. (b) Gas Quantities (i) The Maximum Daily Quantity (MDQ) stated in Dth in the aggregate and the estimated total quantity of Gas to be transported during the requested term of service; and, for each receipt and delivery point requested the maximum daily quantities to be received and delivered at each point. (ii) For Transportation service requested pursuant to Rate Schedule TS Access, the sum of all individual maximum Primary Receipt Point quantities set forth in the Agreement shall not exceed the MDQ in the aggregate, and the sum of all individual maximum Primary Delivery Point quantities set forth in the Agreement shall not exceed the MDQ in the aggregate. (c) Receipt Point(s) The point(s) at which Shipper desires Transporters system to receive Gas. (d) Delivery Point(s) The point(s) on Transporters system at which Shipper desires the delivery of Gas. (e) Term of Service Shipper must request a minimum term of one (1) calendar month. (f) Facilities Shipper must provide a description and the proposed location of any facilities to be constructed or installed by any party affected by the proposed service. (g) Creditworthiness Requirements As a condition of eligibility for Transportation service, a Shipper shall be required to establish and maintain throughout the term of the Transportation service sufficient creditworthiness to satisfy Shippers obligations for the Transportation service, to Transporters reasonable satisfaction. Upon request by Transporter, Shipper shall provide proof of its creditworthiness. Transporter shall be entitled to undertake such credit searches as it deems necessary and appropriate and to require that it receive sufficient information to establish that a potential Shipper is creditworthy. The result of such creditworthiness checks should generally be communicated to the potential Shipper within two (2) weeks of receipt of the completed application. If the potential Shipper is sufficiently creditworthy, no security shall be required. If a potential Shipper cannot establish that it is creditworthy, the creditworthiness requirements can nonetheless be satisfied paying a deposit equal to the total estimated charges for the first three (3) full months of Transportation service. Transporter will have the right to require additional security upon three (3) Business Days notice if conditions for the potential Shipper or Shipper changes in any material way. The types of security that may be required by Transporter are: security deposits; irrevocable letters of credit; guarantees; or such other security as is acceptable to Transporter. Transporter can modify any and all security requirements based upon changes in the potential Shippers or Shippers level of Transportation service. All of Transporters creditworthiness review standards and requirements shall be imposed on a non-discriminatory basis. Security shall no longer be required where Transporter deems that security is no longer needed or when the Shipper is no longer receiving Transportation Service from Transporter. (i) Compliance with Statement of Operating Conditions Shippers request shall include a statement that it is willing to abide by the terms of the applicable rate schedule, including the Statement of Operating Conditions. 7.5 Inadequate Capacity Response to Request. Transporter shall promptly notify a Shipper if it cannot satisfy an otherwise valid request for service due to lack of capacity. 7.6 Interruption of Service. Transporter reserves the right not to offer or commence interruptible interstate service or to discontinue any interruptible interstate services if it determines that such services would impair the ability to provide non-interruptible services to intrastate customers. 7.7 Incomplete or Deficient Requests. In the event a request does not contain the information specified in Section 7.4 hereof, Transporter shall, within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of such request, inform Shipper in writing of the specific items needed to complete a valid request. Shipper shall have fifteen (15) Business Days to provide the specified information. In the event such information is not received within fifteen (15) Business Days or if Shippers request, as supplemented, remains incomplete and deficient, Shippers request shall be null and void. 7.8 Transportation Service Agreement Execution. Unless waived by Transporter, if a Shipper fails to execute and return to Transporter an Agreement which accurately reflects the Shippers submitted request for service within thirty (30) Business Days after such agreement is tendered by Transporter for execution, then the Shippers request and Agreement shall be null and void. In all other circumstances, unless waived by Transporter, a Shippers submitted request for service and Agreement shall be null and void if the Shipper fails to execute and return to Transporter the tendered Agreement within thirty (30) Days after such has been tendered by Transporter for execution. 7.9 Extensions. Prior to the expiration of the term of an existing Agreement, Transporter and the existing Shipper may mutually agree to an extension of the term of the Agreement with respect to all or a part of the underlying capacity. Agreements with evergreen clauses will automatically roll one year unless Transporter receives notification to terminate service one year prior to the Agreement termination date.

8. NOMINATIONS, SCHEDULING, AND CURTAILMENT (continued) 8.1 Nominations. (e) Nomination Deadlines. (i) The standard nominations timeline shall be as follows: 11:30a.m. CCT for receipt of nominations by Transporter; 3:30p.m. CCT on the Day prior to flow for receipt of completed confirmation by Transporter from upstream and downstream connected parties. Transporter will post notification of the confirmation of nominations on its system by 4:30 p.m. CCT. (ii) All nominations are considered to be original nominations and must be replaced in order to be changed. (iii) Nominations received after nomination deadline shall be scheduled after the nominations received before the nomination deadline. (iv) A Shippers failure to submit properly completed nominations may result in Gas not being transported. A Shippers failure to submit a nomination by the applicable deadline may result in delays for the requested service. Late nominations will not be accepted if such acceptance would adversely impact the operation of Transporters Gas system or adversely impact Transporters purchase and receipt of Gas for other system customers. (f) Intraday Nominations. Any nomination submitted after the nomination deadline for the Day of Gas flow as specified in Section 8.1(e)(i) herein shall be treated as an Intraday Nomination. At least one (1) Intraday Nomination can be submitted by 4:00p.m. CCT of the preceding Business Day, subject to confirmation by Transporter and any upstream or downstream pipeline. Transporter may accept Intraday Nominations if it determines that such a change will not adversely impact Transporters system. (g) Same Day Nominations. Any nomination submitted after the deadline for Intraday Nominations will be confirmed on a best efforts basis. The deadline for Same Day Nominations is 7:30a.m. CCT of the Business Day on which the nomination is to take effect, subject to confirmation by Transporter and any upstream or downstream pipeline. Transporter may accept such change to Shippers Nomination if it determines that such a change will not adversely impact Transporters system. (i) Intraday and Same Day Nominations can be used to request increases or decreases in total flow or changes to delivery points of scheduled Gas. (ii) Intraday and Same Day Nominations do not rollover (i.e., Intraday and Same Day Nominations span one (1) Day only). Intraday Nominations do not replace the remainder of a standing nomination. There is no need to re-nominate if the Intraday Nomination modifies existing nomination. (iii) Transporter will not give scheduling priority to service under Intraday Nominations submitted by Shippers. Transporter will not accept or confirm an Intraday Nomination that would result in a change to any other Shippers scheduled and flowing quantities for that Day without their prior consent. Transporter will provide advance notice using the mechanisms provided for in Section 9.6 below for notifying Shippers of OFOs to Shippers of reductions in scheduled and/or flowing quantities resulting from Intraday Nominations by Shippers in accordance with Section 8.1(f) above. Transporter will notify any such Shipper if any penalties will apply on the Day its scheduled and/or flowing quantities are reduced. If Transporter does not notify a Shipper in advance of reductions in scheduled and/or flowing quantities due to an Intraday Nomination by a Shipper, no penalties will be imposed by Transporter on such Shipper for the Day of the reduction. No penalties other than penalties assessed during periods in which OFOs and/or curtailment orders are in effect will be imposed by Transporter on Shippers whose scheduled and/or flowing quantities were reduced due to Shippers Intraday Nominations. (iv) Intraday and same Day Nominations, if scheduled, will take effect at the start of the next Gas Day, 9a.m. CCT. (h) Nomination Confirmation. Transporter shall contact the appropriate upstream and downstream parties to confirm the nominated quantities. (i) Confirmation of Nominations. For nominations to take effect on the next calendar Day of the month after the nomination deadline has passed, Transporter will contact the upstream pipeline or Point Operator for confirmation of Gas deliveries to Transporter, and the downstream pipeline or Point Operator for confirmation of Gas receipts from Transporter. The confirmation process will be completed between Transporter and the appropriate pipeline or Point Operator by 3:30p.m. CCT. Transporter will make available to Shippers by 4:30p.m. CCT all scheduled and confirmed quantities. At a receipt or delivery point, the lesser of rule (confirmed or nominated flow) applies when confirming. If no communication is received, the lesser of the new nomination or previously scheduled quantity applies. (ii) After each Gas flow Day, Transporter shall promptly make available to Shippers information containing scheduled quantities, including scheduled Intraday Nominations and any other scheduling changes. (iii) Curtailment and Interruptions in Service. Transporter shall notify Shipper(s) affected by interruptions in service or curtailment pursuant to Section 8.3 of the General Terms and Conditions as soon as practicable. Transporter shall also notify the affected Shipper(s) as soon as practicable of the resumption of service, and upon such notification, Shipper shall verify the level of service desired. Transporter may require a Shipper to submit a completed nomination specifying the level of service desired. 8.2 Scheduling Procedures. (a) Transportation services shall be scheduled in the following order, from highest to lowest priority: (i) All services, in the following order, from highest to lowest priority; (1) Services utilizing primary Receipt Points for redelivery to primary Delivery Points; (2) Services utilizing primary Receipt Points for redelivery to secondary Delivery Points; (ii) In the event there is insufficient capacity available to schedule service, Transporter shall first schedule interruptible services for which the maximum rate is to be paid. Transporter shall next schedule discounted interruptible services based on the rate to be paid, from highest to lowest, with service for which the highest rate is to be paid scheduled first. (iii) In the event there is insufficient capacity to schedule all such services at the same rate, Transporter shall allocate the available capacity pro rata based upon confirmed nominations. (b) Nominations to make up imbalance quantities may be denied if all other services cannot be scheduled. (c) Transporter will not give scheduling priority to Intraday Nominations submitted by Shippers. Transporter shall notify any Shipper whose service is to be interrupted pursuant to this provision in accordance with Section 8.1 (i) above. 8.3 Curtailment of Services. (a) Transporter reserves the right to impose, at any time, any reasonable conditions upon the Transportation of Shippers Gas which Transporter, in its sole good faith judgment, deems necessary to maintain the safe and efficient operation of its distribution system, or to make the operating terms and conditions of service hereunder compatible with those of its suppliers (upstream interstate or RNG suppliers). Under such circumstances, the following conditions shall apply: (i) Any Shipper that does not comply with a notice of operational curtailment shall be subject to, in addition to any otherwise applicable charges, a penalty of $10 per therm for all unauthorized quantities during the curtailment period. (ii) Transporter shall endeavor to provide notice of such operational curtailment 48 hours prior to the commencement of the applicable Gas Day. (iii) Notwithstanding condition (ii), Transporter may impose an operational curtailment on the current Gas Day. In the event an operational curtailment is imposed on the current Gas Day, a minimum one-hour grace period will be allowed before penalties begin to apply. (iv) A Shipper will not be charged for incremental upstream pipeline charges or penalties incurred by the Transporter as a result of the Shippers compliance with a notice of operation curtailment. (b) Notices and Indemnification. Transporter shall have the responsibility to inform only its Shippers and the immediate upstream or downstream facility operators involved in a transaction of any curtailment or interruption. Curtailed Shippers shall indemnify Transporter against and hold Transporter harmless from any and all damages, claims, suits, actions or proceedings whatsoever threatened or initiated as a result of any curtailment or interruption invoked by Transporter, which shall include any curtailment or interruptions described in any part of this section; provided, however, Shippers shall not be required to indemnify Transporter for any damages resulting from Transporters gross negligence or willful misconduct. 8.4 Receipt of Gas. Departures from the scheduled deliveries at the Point of Receipt shall be kept to the minimum permitted by operating conditions and shall be balanced as soon as practicable. 8.5 Delivery of Gas. Based upon the daily quantities scheduled, such information may be a vailable concerning the quantities actually received, and after making adjustment for any prior imbalance in deliveries, Transporter shall make daily delivery, to the extent practicable, of Thermally Equivalent Quantities of Gas at the Point of Delivery. 8.6 Constant Rates. Shipper shall deliver all Gas for Transportation hereunder at uniform hourly rates as and when operationally feasible throughout each Day and throughout each month. 8.7 Adjustments to Thermally Equivalent Quantities. Each month, Transporter shall calculate the actual quantity of Gas transported by Shipper. Shipper shall be responsible for maintaining a balance between quantities of Gas received and quantities of Gas delivered, adjusted for appropriate Fuel Use and LUFG quantities. For the purposes of this provision, an Accumulated Imbalance shall mean the cumulative difference between receipts and deliveries under the Agreement since the date of initial service; Tolerance Level shall mean the greater of 50 Dth or five percent (5%) of the total quantity of Gas delivered by Transporter to Shipper during each month of service; Imbalance Penalty Quantity shall mean the Accumulated Imbalance in excess of the Tolerance Level. If, at the end of each month of service, Shipper shall have an Accumulated Imbalance in excess of the Tolerance Level, Transporter shall apply a balancing charge upon the Imbalance Penalty Quantity in the following manner: (a) Transporter shall notify Shipper of any Accumulated Imbalance including any Imbalance Penalty Quantity with the monthly billing pursuant to Section 11.1 of the General Terms and Conditions. In the event that Shipper does not reduce the Accumulated Imbalance to within the Tolerance Level within 30 Days from the date Shipper was notified, Transporter shall charge Shipper in the next monthly billing pursuant to Section 10.1 of the General Terms and Conditions of the Statement of Operating Conditions an additional charge of $1.00 per Dth multiplied by the Imbalance Penalty Quantity during each month following such 30-Day notice period that an Accumulated Imbalance exists that exceeds the Tolerance Level. This balancing charge will be assessed each month until the imbalance is corrected in accordance with this provision, and subsequently at any time and from time-to-time that an Accumulated Imbalance has occurred under the Agreement. (b) In the event the quantities of Gas received and to be delivered are not in balance on a thermal equivalent basis at the end of the term hereof, Shipper will balance any final imbalance within 60 Days of the date that Transporter notifies Shipper of any final imbalance. If, at the end of such final balancing period, Shipper has a positive imbalance and has not scheduled the delivery of said quantities with Transporter, Transporter will retain those quantities free and clear of any adverse claims. If, at the end of such final balancing period, Shipper owes Transporter quantities of Gas which Shipper has not delivered, Shipper will pay to Transporter an amount equal to the monthly index price as published in Inside FERC Gas Market Report for SoCal Gas for the month after service was terminated. 9. SYSTEM MANAGEMENT 9.1 Responsibility of Transporter. Transporter will at all times maintain operational control of all of its transmission and other facilities. Transporter shall endeavor to preserve the overall operational integrity of its system; provided, however, that Transporter shall not be obligated to buy or sell Gas or to install additional compression or otherwise modify its system for these purposes. Operating personnel for Shippers and other entities which are physically taking delivery of Gas from Transporter or tendering Gas to Transporter shall cooperate with Transporter in furtherance of this Section 9. Each Shipper shall designate one or more persons for Transporter to contact on operating matters at any time, 24 hours a Day, every Day. If Transporter cannot contact any Shipper because that Shippers contact person is unavailable, such Shipper shall be solely responsible for any consequences arising from such failure of communication. 9.2 System Integrity. For the purpose of this Section 9, the overall operational integrity of Transporter's system shall encompass the integrity of the physical system and the preservation of physical assets and their performance, the overall operating performance of the entire physical system (or any portion thereof), and the maintenance (on a reliable and operationally sound basis) of adequate system pressure, total system deliverability and the quality of Gas delivered. 9.3 System Resources. Transporter shall have the unqualified right to utilize all system resources to alleviate conditions which threaten the overall operational integrity of Transporters system, or to provide services as set forth in this Statement of Operating Conditions. Transporter may buy and sell Gas to the extent necessary to maintain system pressure and line pack, and to perform other functions of Transporter in connection with Transportation services. Nothing herein shall impose on Transporter any obligation to provide a supply function to any of its Transportation Shippers; provided however, that Transporter may rely on line pack to provide instantaneous receipt and delivery and tolerances as applicable under any rate schedule. Transporter shall not be liable to any person for actions taken for these purposes except for Transporters negligence or undue discrimination. 10. BILLING 10.1 Billing. On or before the 10th Day of each month, Transporter shall render to Shipper a statement of the total amount of Gas delivered to Transporter by Shipper at the Point of Delivery hereunder during the preceding month and the amount due. When information necessary for billing purposes is in the control of Shipper, Shipper shall furnish such information to Transporter on or before the 10th Day of the month. Shipper and Transporter shall have the right to examine at reasonable hours the books, records, and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, charge, or computation made under or pursuant to any of the provisions hereof. If any examination reveals any inaccuracy in any statement or charge, then necessary adjustment and correction thereof shall be made promptly, provided that no adjustment for any billing or payment shall be made after the lapse of six (6) months from the date of the invoice or statement thereof unless prior thereto the adjustment is made or the error is challenged in writing including documentation as to the basis and reasons for the claimed error. 10.2 Payment. Shipper shall pay Transporter, at its general office, or at such other address as Transporter shall designate, on or before the 25th Day of the month, the amount due for the preceding month. If presentation of a bill by Transporter is delayed after the 10th Day of the month, then the time of payment shall be extended accordingly unless Shipper is responsible for such delay. Should Shipper fail to pay all or any portion of the amount of any bill as herein provided when such amount is due, interest on the unpaid portion of the bill shall accrue at a rate (which in no event shall be higher than the maximum rate permitted by applicable law) equal to the current FERC Gas Interest Rate, from the date due until the date of payment. If such failure to pay continues for 30 Days after payment is due, Transporter, in addition to any other remedy it may have hereunder, may suspend further receipt/delivery of Gas until such amount is paid; provided, however, if Shipper in good faith shall dispute the amount of any such bill or part thereof and shall pay to Transporter such amount as it concedes to be correct and, at any time thereafter within 30 Days of a demand made by Transporter, shall furnish a good and sufficient surety bond, in an amount and with surety satisfactory to Transporter, guaranteeing payment to Transporter of the amount ultimately found due upon such bills after a final determination which may be reached either by agreement or judgment of the courts, as may be the case, then Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery of Gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond or otherwise hereunder. 10.3 Adjustment of Billing Errors. If it shall be found that at any time or times Shipper has been overcharged or undercharged in any form whatsoever under the provisions hereof and Shipper shall have actually paid the bill containing such overcharge or undercharge, then within 30 Days after the final determination thereof, Transporter shall refund the amount of any such overcharge and Shipper shall pay the amount of any such undercharge. In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within 30 Days of the determination thereof, provided that claim therefore shall have been made within 30 Days from the date of discovery of such error, but in any event within 12 months from the date of delivery of such statement. If the parties are unable to agree on the adjustment of any claimed error, any resort by either of the parties to legal procedure, either at law, in equity, or otherwise, shall be commenced within 12 months after the supposed cause of action is alleged to have arisen or shall thereafter be forever barred. 10.4 Tax Obligations. Shipper shall pay to Transporter any applicable energy, value added, sales or use tax, or similar tax, and any penalty and interest imposed on Shipper by the federal government, any state, or by any political subdivision of a state, which amount Transporter is obligated by law to collect and remit. Payment shall be at the applicable rate prescribed by law. If Shipper is exempt from the obligation to pay such taxes, Shipper shall provide Transporter with documentation establishing that exemption. 11. ALLOCATION OF LIABILITIES 11.1 Responsibility for Gas. As between Transporter and Shipper, Shipper shall be in exclusive control and possession of the Gas until such has been delivered to Transporter at the Point of Receipt and after such Gas has been redelivered to or for the account of Shipper by Transporter at the Point of Delivery. Transporter shall be in exclusive control and possession of such Gas while it is in the System between the Point of Receipt and the Point of Delivery. Transporter shall have no liability while the Gas is in the exclusive control of Shipper and Shipper will have no liability, except for damage, loss or injury caused by Shippers delivery of Gas that does not meet the quality specifications set forth in the Statement of Operating Conditions, the ACC tariff for Transporters System including any quality specification in the Arizona Administrative Code, and/or other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter, while the Gas is in the exclusive control of Transporter. 11.2 Indemnification. The party in exclusive possession shall indemnify and hold harmless the other party, its officers, agents, employees and contractors from and against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorneys fees and court costs) or encumbrances whatsoever, including injury and death of persons, arising directly or indirectly during such possession of the Gas; provided, neither Transporter nor Shipper shall be liable for the gross negligence of willful misconduct of the other party. 12. WARRANTY 12.1 Warranty. Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns that it will have at the time of delivery of Gas to Transporter at the Point of Receipt for Transportation hereunder a good and merchantable Title to all Gas tendered for service under this operating statement. Transporter warrants for itself, its successors and assigns that it will at the time of delivery to others of the Gas transported hereunder have good right to deliver such Gas to others. Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns that the Gas it warrants hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims whatsoever, that it will indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of any adverse claims of any and all persons to said Gas and/or to royalties, taxes, license fees, or charges thereon which are applicable to such delivery of Gas and that it will indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all taxes of assessments which may be levied and assessed upon such delivery and which are by law payable by, and the obligation of, the party making such delivery. 13. FORCE MAJEURE 13.1 Force Majeure. If by reason of force majeure either party hereto is rendered unable, wholly or in part, to carry out its obligations under this agreement, and if such party gives notice and reasonably full particulars of such force majeure in writing or by facsimile to the other within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the party giving such notice, so far as and to the extent that it is affected by such force majeure, shall not be liable in damages during the continuance of an inability so caused, provided such cause shall so far as possible be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. 13.2 Definition. The term amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;force majeureamp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;amp; as employed herein shall mean acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of the public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, plagues, epidemics, pandemics, outbreaks of infectious disease or any other public health crisis, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, hurricanes, storms, floods, washouts, arrests, priority limitation or restraining orders of any kind of the government of the United States or a State or of any civil or military authority, civil disturbances, explosions, lines of pipe, freezing of wells or lines or pipe, partial or entire failure of natural gas wells including breakage, accidents, emergency tests, unplanned maintenance or repairs to machinery or storage wells, inability to obtain or unavoidable delay in obtaining material and equipment, interruption of service under any necessary Transportation or exchange agreement affecting service under the applicable Agreement and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension. 13.3 Limitations. Such force majeure affecting the performance hereunder by either Shipper or Transporter, however, shall not relieve such party of liability in the event of concurring negligence or in the event of failure to use due diligence to remedy the situation and to remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch, nor shall such causes or contingencies affecting such performance relieve either party from its obligations to make payments as determined hereunder. 14. NOTICES 14.1 Notices. Except as herein or in the Agreement otherwise provided, any notice, request, demand, statement, bill, or payment provided for, or any notice which either party may desire to give to the other, shall be in writing and shall be considered as being delivered when mailed by registered or certified mail return receipt requested to the Post Office Address of the parties hereto; such Post Office Address shall be set forth in the Agreement. Routine communications, including monthly statements and payments, shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed by registered, certified or ordinary mail, by email, or posted on Transporters internet website. 15. TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (TS) ACCESS AGREEMENT 15.1 Form of Transportation Service Agreement. Shipper shall enter into a contract with Transporter under Transporters applicable standard form of Agreement, a copy of which is attached hereto as Exhibit A and made a part hereof. 15.2 Term. All Transportation services shall be deemed to have been terminated upon the expiration or termination of the contracts governing such services unless otherwise extended by a mutual agreement by Shipper providing written notice of an intent to extend received within 6 months prior to expiration of Agreements for primary terms greater than 1 year and 3 months prior to expiration of Agreements for primary terms less than one year. 15.3 Evergreen Provision. Transporter shall offer on a basis that is not unduly discriminatory to all Shippers that agree to contract for Transportation service with Transporter for a primary contract term of one year or more the following evergreen provision: This Agreement shall become effective as of _______ and shall continue for a primary term ending ________; provided, however, that this Agreement shall continue to be in effect thereafter unless and until terminated by either Transporter or Shipper by written notice to the other delivered at least one (1) year prior to the date of intended termination. 15.4 Quantity Obligations and Requirements. At the time of execution of the Agreement, Transporter and Shipper shall agree upon the quantities of Gas to be transported. 16. REGULATIONS 16.1 Regulatory Authority. This Agreement, and all terms and provisions contained herein, and the respective obligations of the parties hereunder, are subject to valid laws, orders, rules, and regulations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction. In the event that any provision of the Statement of Operating Conditions is found to be inconsistent with or contrary to any federal, state or local laws, regulations, rules or orders, then, to the extent possible, the Statement of Operating Conditions shall be modified to comply with such ruling. 17. OBLIGATION TO CONTINUE SERVICE 17.1 Failure to Comply. Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue service under any of the rate schedules of this Statement of Operating Conditions on behalf of any Shipper which, within ten (10) Days after receipt of written notice from Transporter, fails to comply with any and all of the terms of the applicable rate schedule, the Statement of Operating Conditions, or with the terms of its Agreement(s) with Transporter or other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter. Notwithstanding the other provisions of the applicable rate schedule, Transporter shall have the right to take immediate unilateral action to protect the integrity of its system in the event Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, determines that immediate or irreparable harm to Transporters facilities or operations will be caused by Shippers failure to comply with any of the terms of the applicable rate schedule, the Statement of Operating Conditions, or with the terms of the applicable Agreement or other agreements that may be in place between the producer of the Gas and Transporter. 17.2 Applicable Law. All of the provisions of these General Terms and Conditions are hereby expressly made subject to all present and future applicable federal or state laws, orders, rules and regulations of governmental authorities having jurisdiction. Except as otherwise provided herein, in the event any provision of these General Terms and Conditions is found to be inconsistent with or contrary to any law, order, rule or regulation, the latter shall be deemed to control and these General Terms and Conditions, to the extent possible, shall be regarded as modified accordingly and as so modified shall continue in full force and effect. The parties hereto recognize that Transporter has entered into transactions hereunder based on its good faith understanding that all acts, obligations, and services performed or to be performed by Transporter hereunder, and the rates therefore, are exempt from the regulation of the FERC or any successor federal governmental authority, except as provided by Sections 284.123 and 284.224 of the FERCs regulations. Transporter reserves the right to terminate immediately the offering or furnishing of any service hereunder if, in Transporters judgment, any governmental act occurs which would require Transporter to offer or furnish service hereunder or which would cause any impairment in Transporters ability to furnish or continue any service hereunder or require Transporter to offer additional intrastate services. Any and all service transactions hereunder must be interstate service eligible under, and shall be fully subject to, the applicable requirements of Section 284.224 of the FERCs rules and regulations, Shippers request for service shall constitute its warranty that Shipper satisfies such requirements, and Transporter shall have the right to request information from any Shipper to verify the eligibility thereunder. 17.3 Existing Facilities. This Transportation service will be available on existing facilities of Transporter except as otherwise agreed. Transporter shall not be required, at its own expense, to install any facilities of any kind to serve a Shipper under this Statement of Operating Conditions. In the event that any new or altered facilities are required to serve a Shipper, said Shipper shall execute a contract for the construction of new facilities and shall pay for all costs of additional facilities, including without limitation, storage, transmission, distribution or metering facilities. 18. WAIVERS 18.1 Performance and Compliance Waivers. Transporter may waive any defaults by any Shipper with respect to performance or compliance with the provisions of the applicable rate schedules on a basis which is not unduly discriminatory; provided, however, that no waiver shall operate or be construed as a waiver of any other or further defaults, whether of a like or different character. Moreover, Transporter may waive, modify or supplement the terms and conditions set forth in this Statement of Operating Conditions or any Agreement, without undue discrimination or preference, and without consent from any Shippers, when in Transporters reasonable judgment such action is necessary or appropriate or consistent with reasonable business practices and Transporter shall have no liability to any Shipper for any such action. 19. ASSIGNMENTS 19.1 Assignments. (a) Assignable Parties. A Shipper may assign its Agreement to: (i) Any person, firm, or corporation acquiring all, or substantially all, of the business Shipper; (ii) An entity that causes Transporter to be financially indifferent to the assignment; and/or (iii) A trustee or trustees, individual or corporate, as security for bonds or other obligations or securities; but
